s and Nonconformists in the 16th–17th centuries, too late to have had much influence on surname formationm in Britain, except in Wales."],"variants":[{"name":"Amoss","meanings":["English: variant of   Amos  ."]},{"name":"Amis","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Ames  ."]}]},{"name":"Manerva","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Found as a female baptismal name. So named from Minerva, goddess of wisdom, war, and all the liberal arts. The name, according to Quintilianus, was formerly Menerva, which is thought to be from meneo or meno, for moneo, to advise. Littleton gives ' menervo, moneo, antiqua vox; unde promt\" nervat, monet, in Saliari carmine, Seal., et Menerva ap. vett. quae postea Minerva.'"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Manerva Amos was born in 1420, in Bramford, Suffolk, England, her father, David Amos, was 20 and her mother, Nancy Watkins, was 20. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Collins. She died about 1470, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1420–Abt 1470":"1420–umbes 1470","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1435–1534":"1435–1534","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1435":"1435","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","Aft 1420":"pärast 1420","1470":"1470","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Downton, Hampshire, England":"Downton, Hampshire, England","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, E